<item>
  <title>Internal Rate of Return (IRR)</title>
  <link>https://thingsishouldknowasafinanceworker.wordpress.com/2015/01/05/internal-rate-of-return-irr/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 05 Jan 2015 21:39:33 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>mrd3v3l0p3r</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://thingsishouldknowasafinanceworker.wordpress.com/?p=9</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<ul>
	<li>The <em>IRR</em> is the interest rate which discounts a known series of future cashflows to achieve a specific <em>NPV</em></li>
	<li>It is therefore also equivalent to the interest rate which discounts a series of cashflows (future <em>and present</em>) to achieve an <em>NPV</em> of 0</li>
	<li>When calculating investment performance <em>IRR</em> is known as the <em>money-weighted rate of return,</em> as it puts greater weight on the period where the amount invested is larger</li>
</ul>
<h6><a title="ACCA THE INTERNAL RATE OF RETURN" href="http://www.accaglobal.com/uk/en/student/foundation-lvl-qual-student-journey/qualification-resources/foundation-lvl-qual/cat-qualification/ffm/ffm-technical-articles/the-internal-rate-of-return.html">ACCA THE INTERNAL RATE OF RETURN</a></h6>
<h6><a title="GitHub" href="https://github.com/tsasioglu/Finance/blob/master/Finance/Calculators/IrCalculator.cs">GitHub</a></h6>]]></content:encoded>
