<item>
  <title>Historical Rate Rollover</title>
  <link>https://thingsishouldknowasafinanceworker.wordpress.com/2015/01/13/historical-rate-rollover/</link>
  <pubDate>Tue, 13 Jan 2015 21:29:58 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>mrd3v3l0p3r</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://thingsishouldknowasafinanceworker.wordpress.com/?p=11</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<ul>
	<li>Rolling of a matured forward transaction at the same rate as the original deal</li>
	<li>Useful contract term for corporates that have a foreign exchange exposure in the future, but do not know the exact date</li>
	<li>Rolling the contract at an old, non-market rate results in it having intrinsic value. It is the effectively a loan between the counterparties, and subsequently a disguised position</li>
	<li>It’s therefore discouraged, or banned, in many markets</li>
</ul>
<h6><a title="Historical-Rate Rollovers: A Dangerous Practice" href="http://www.newyorkfed.org/fxc/annualreports/ar1995/fxar9526.html">Historical-Rate Rollovers: A Dangerous Practice</a></h6>]]></content:encoded>
